{"title_page": "Willibald Eser", "text_new": "{{more citations needed|date=May 2019}}\n{{Expand German|date=December 2015}}\n'''Willibald Eser''' (1 September 1933 - August 2005) was a German screenwriter, notable for his work on films including ''[[A Glass of Water (1960 film)|A Glass of Water]]'', ''[[Love from Paris]]'', ''[[Temptation in the Summer Wind]]'' and ''[[The Dream of Lieschen Mueller]]''.\n\n==Selected filmography==\n* ''[[Love from Paris]]'' (1957)\n* ''[[The Count of Luxemburg (1957 film)|The Count of Luxemburg]]'' (1957)\n* ''[[A Glass of Water (1960 film)|A Glass of Water]]'' (1960)\n* ''[[Ingeborg (film)|Ingeborg]]'' (1960)\n* ''[[The Dream of Lieschen Mueller]]'' (1961)\n* ''[[How I Learned to Love Women]]'' (1966)\n* ''[[Slap in the Face (film)|Slap in the Face]]'' (1970)\n* ''[[Temptation in the Summer Wind]]'' (1972)\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDB name|0260552}}\n*http://www.welt.de/print-welt/article162078/Drehbuchautor-Willibald-Eser-gestorben.html{{dead link|date=May 2019}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Eser, Willibald}}\n[[Category:German screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:1933 births]]\n[[Category:2005 deaths]]\n\n\n{{Screen-writer-stub}}\n{{Germany-writer-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{more citations needed|date=May 2019}}\n{{Expand German|date=December 2015}}\n'''Willibald Eser''' (1 September 1933 - August 2005) was a German screenwriter, notable for his work on films including ''[[A Glass of Water (1960 film)|A Glass of Water]]'', ''[[Love from Paris]]'', ''[[Temptation in the Summer Wind]]'' and ''[[The Dream of Lieschen Mueller]]''.\n\n==Selected filmography==\n* ''[[Love from Paris]]'' (1957)\n* ''[[The Count of Luxemburg (1957 film)|The Count of Luxemburg]]'' (1957)\n* ''[[A Glass of Water (1960 film)|A Glass of Water]]'' (1960)\n* ''[[Ingeborg (film)|Ingeborg]]'' (1960)\n* ''[[The Dream of Lieschen Mueller]]'' (1961)\n* ''[[How I Learned to Love Women]]'' (1966)\n* ''[[Slap in the Face (film)|Slap in the Face]]'' (1970)\n* ''[[Temptation in the Summer Wind]]'' (1972)\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDB name|0260552}}\n*http://www.welt.de/print-welt/article162078/Drehbuchautor-Willibald-Eser-gestorben.html{{dead link|date=May 2019}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Eser, Willibald}}\n{{Screen-writer-stub}}\n{{Germany-writer-stub}}\n[[category:German screenwriters]]\n[[category:Male screenwriters]]\n[[category:1933 births]]\n[[category:2005 deaths]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Willibald_Eser"}
{"title_page": "The Guitar World According to Frank Zappa", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name         = The Guitar World According to Frank Zappa\n| type         = compilation\n| artist       = [[Frank Zappa]]\n| cover        = The Guitar World According to Frank Zappa.jpg\n| alt          = \n| released     = 13 april 1987\n| recorded     = 1972\u20141984\n| venue        = \n| studio       = \n| genre        = [[Instrumental rock]]\n| length       = 32:08\n| label        = [[Barking Pumpkin Records|Barking Pumpkin]]\n| producer     = [[Frank Zappa]]\n| prev_title   = [[Mothermania]]\n| prev_year    = 1969\n| next_title   = [[Strictly Commercial]]\n| next_year    = 1995\n}}\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1      = [[Allmusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.allmusic.com/album/r53182/review |title=The Guitar World According To Frank Zappa - Frank Zappa &#124; AllMusic |first=W. |last=Ruhlmann |work=allmusic.com |year=2011 |accessdate=22 July 2011}}</ref>\n| rev2      = \n| rev2Score = \n}}\n'''''The Guitar World According to Frank Zappa''''' is a 1987 [[compilation album]] featuring [[guitar]] solos by [[Frank Zappa]]. It was issued as a [[Compact audio cassette|cassette]] from [[Guitar World]] magazine, and has also been available in bootlegged versions as ''Guitar Hernia'' and ''Solo on Guitar''. The cassette contains some unique material, including different takes and an excerpt from an unreleased remix of \"Revised Music for Guitar and Low-Budget Orchestra\" from the ''[[Studio Tan]]'' album, featuring drum overdubs by [[Chad Wackerman]]. The album was released on vinyl in April 2019 as part of [[Record Store Day]].<ref>{{cite web|url= https://recordstoreday.com/SpecialRelease/10855 |title=THE GUITAR WORLD ACCORDING TO FRANK ZAPPA}}</ref> \n\nSimilar compilations of Zappa guitar solos include [[Guitar (Frank Zappa album)|Guitar]], [[Trance-Fusion]], [[Frank Zappa Plays the Music of Frank Zappa: A Memorial Tribute]], [[Shut Up 'n Play Yer Guitar]], and [[One Shot Deal]].\n\n==Track listing==\n\n===Side one===\n#\"[[Sleep Dirt (instrumental)|Sleep Dirt]]\" \u2013 3:17\n#*From the ''[[Sleep Dirt]]'' album.\n#\"Friendly Little Finger\" \u2013 4:17\n#*From the ''[[Zoot Allures]]'' album.\n#Excerpt from \"Revised Music for Guitar and Low-Budget Orchestra\" \u2013 1:45 [booklet lists incorrectly 2:21]\n#*Unreleased remix with drum overdubs from 1984.\n#\"Things That Look Like Meat\" \u2013 6:06\n#*Shortened version of a track later released on the ''[[Guitar (Frank Zappa album)|Guitar]]'' album.\n\n===Side two===\n#\"Down in de Dew\" \u2013 2:54\n#*Later released as part of the ''[[L\u00e4ther]]'' box set.\n#\"A Solo from Heidelberg\" \u2013 5:26\n#*Later released on the [[One Shot Deal]] album.\n#\"A Solo from Cologne\" \u2013 5:11\n#*Longer version of a track later released on the ''[[Guitar (Frank Zappa album)|Guitar]]'' album.\n#\"A Solo from Atlanta\" \u2013 4:05\n#*Longer version of a track later released on the ''[[Guitar (Frank Zappa album)|Guitar]]'' album.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://globalia.net/donlope/fz/lyrics/compilations/Guitar_World.html Compilations discography]\n*[http://www.lukpac.org/~handmade/patio/weirdo/weirdo.html#guitarworld Weirdo discography]\n\n{{Frank Zappa albums}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Guitar World According to Frank Zappa}}\n[[Category:1987 compilation albums]]\n[[Category:Barking Pumpkin Records albums]]\n[[Category:Compilation albums included with magazines]]\n[[Category:Frank Zappa compilation albums]]\n\n{{1980s-compilation-album-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name         = The Guitar World According to Frank Zappa\n| type         = compilation\n| artist       = [[Frank Zappa]]\n| cover        = The Guitar World According to Frank Zappa.jpg\n| alt          = \n| released     = 13 april 1987\n| recorded     = 1972\u20141984\n| venue        = \n| studio       = \n| genre        = [[Instrumental rock]]\n| length       = 32:08\n| label        = [[Barking Pumpkin Records|Barking Pumpkin]]\n| producer     = [[Frank Zappa]]\n| prev_title   = [[Mothermania]]\n| prev_year    = 1969\n| next_title   = [[Strictly Commercial]]\n| next_year    = 1995\n}}\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1      = [[Allmusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.allmusic.com/album/r53182/review |title=The Guitar World According To Frank Zappa - Frank Zappa &#124; AllMusic |first=W. |last=Ruhlmann |work=allmusic.com |year=2011 |accessdate=22 July 2011}}</ref>\n| rev2      = \n| rev2Score = \n}}\n'''''The Guitar World According to Frank Zappa''''' is a 1987 [[compilation album]] featuring [[guitar]] solos by [[Frank Zappa]]. It was issued as a [[Compact audio cassette|cassette]] from [[Guitar World]] magazine, and has also been available in bootlegged versions as ''Guitar Hernia'' and ''Solo on Guitar''. The cassette contains some unique material, including different takes and an excerpt from an unreleased remix of \"Revised Music for Guitar and Low-Budget Orchestra\" from the ''[[Studio Tan]]'' album, featuring drum overdubs by [[Chad Wackerman]]. The album was released on vinyl in April 2019 as part of [[Record Store Day]]<ref>{{cite web|url= https://recordstoreday.com/SpecialRelease/10855 |title=THE GUITAR WORLD ACCORDING TO FRANK ZAPPA}}</ref>. \n\nSimilar compilations of Zappa guitar solos include [[Guitar (Frank Zappa album)|Guitar]], [[Trance-Fusion]], [[Frank Zappa Plays the Music of Frank Zappa: A Memorial Tribute]], [[Shut Up 'n Play Yer Guitar]], and [[One Shot Deal]].\n\n==Track listing==\n\n===Side one===\n#\"[[Sleep Dirt (instrumental)|Sleep Dirt]]\" \u2013 3:17\n#*From the ''[[Sleep Dirt]]'' album.\n#\"Friendly Little Finger\" \u2013 4:17\n#*From the ''[[Zoot Allures]]'' album.\n#Excerpt from \"Revised Music for Guitar and Low-Budget Orchestra\" \u2013 1:45 [booklet lists incorrectly 2:21]\n#*Unreleased remix with drum overdubs from 1984.\n#\"Things That Look Like Meat\" \u2013 6:06\n#*Shortened version of a track later released on the ''[[Guitar (Frank Zappa album)|Guitar]]'' album.\n\n===Side two===\n#\"Down in de Dew\" \u2013 2:54\n#*Later released as part of the ''[[L\u00e4ther]]'' box set.\n#\"A Solo from Heidelberg\" \u2013 5:26\n#*Later released on the [[One Shot Deal]] album.\n#\"A Solo from Cologne\" \u2013 5:11\n#*Longer version of a track later released on the ''[[Guitar (Frank Zappa album)|Guitar]]'' album.\n#\"A Solo from Atlanta\" \u2013 4:05\n#*Longer version of a track later released on the ''[[Guitar (Frank Zappa album)|Guitar]]'' album.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://globalia.net/donlope/fz/lyrics/compilations/Guitar_World.html Compilations discography]\n*[http://www.lukpac.org/~handmade/patio/weirdo/weirdo.html#guitarworld Weirdo discography]\n\n{{Frank Zappa albums}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Guitar World According to Frank Zappa}}\n[[Category:1987 compilation albums]]\n[[Category:Barking Pumpkin Records albums]]\n[[Category:Compilation albums included with magazines]]\n[[Category:Frank Zappa compilation albums]]\n\n{{1980s-compilation-album-stub}}\n", "name_user": "DannyS712", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing the location of periods / full stops", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Guitar_World_According_to_Frank_Zappa"}
{"title_page": "The Glitch Mob", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name             = The Glitch Mob\n| image            = The Glitch Mob 2014.jpg\n| caption          = The Glitch Mob performing in 2014\n| landscape        = yes\n| background       = group_or_band\n| origin           = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], United States\n| genre            = {{flatlist|\n* [[Glitch (music)|Glitch]] \n* [[electronica]] \n* [[Intelligent dance music|IDM]]\n*[[Industrial music|industrial]]\n}}\n| years_active     = 2006\u2013present\n| label            = Glass Air Records\n| website          = {{URL|theglitchmob.com}}\n| current_members  = [[edIT (musician)|edIT]] (Edward Ma)<br/>Boreta (Justin Boreta)<br/>Ooah (Josh Mayer)\n| past_members     = Kraddy (Matthew Kratz)<br/>Kitty-D (David Altamira)\n}}\n\n'''The Glitch Mob''' is an American [[electronic music]] group from [[Los Angeles]], [[California]]. It consists of [[Edit (musician)|edIT]] (Edward Ma), [[Boreta]] (Justin Boreta) and [[Ooah]] (Josh Mayer). Chris Martins of ''[[LA Weekly]]'' noted that they \"have undoubtedly found the largest audience of any L.A. beat scene artist yet.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Martins|first=Chris|title=Beat Music Goes Big Time: Glitch Mob & Fighting Gravity Make Semi-Finals on America's Got Talent|url=http://blogs.laweekly.com/westcoastsound/2010/09/glitch_mob_fighting_gravity_americas_got_talent.php|accessdate=23 February 2011|newspaper=[[LA Weekly]]|date=1 September 2010}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe Glitch Mob, originally a four-piece including [[Kraddy]], was formed within the burgeoning Los Angeles bass-driven 'beat' scene. The group made a name for themselves playing live, choosing to perform with laptops and MIDI controllers like the [[Lemur Input Device|Lemur]].<ref name=Sea>{{cite news|last=Brown|first=August|title=The Glitch Mob swims in a vast, ominous 'Sea'|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/music_blog/2010/06/the-glitch-mob-swims-in-a-vast-ominous-sea.html|accessdate=23 February 2011|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=11 June 2010}}</ref><ref name=CDM>{{cite web|last=Kirn|first=Peter|title=The Glitch Mob: Tour, Free Single Download, Multiple Laptops + Lemurs|url=http://createdigitalmusic.com/2010/03/the-glitch-mob-tour-free-single-download-multiple-laptops-lemurs/|work=Create Digital Music|date=25 March 2010|accessdate=23 February 2011}}</ref> They won fans through showcasing their chosen technology during solo performances, and after gaining attention in Los Angeles and San Francisco, the group eventually toured more widely along the West Coast and then to various festivals worldwide.<ref name=URB>{{cite web|last=Levine|first=Noah|title=Live Review: The Glitch Mob @ Double Door (05.01.10)|url=http://www.urb.com/2010/05/03/live-review-the-glitch-mob-double-door-05-01-10/|work=[[URB (magazine)|URB]]|date=3 May 2010|accessdate=23 February 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100924152233/http://www.urb.com/2010/05/03/live-review-the-glitch-mob-double-door-05-01-10/|archivedate=24 September 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref> After citing \"creative differences,\" founding member Kraddy left the group in 2009.<ref name=XLR8R>{{cite news|last=Marston|first=Jennifer|title=Kraddy Departs from The Glitch Mob|url=https://www.xlr8r.com/news/2009/06/kraddy-departs-from-the-glitch-mob|accessdate=23 February 2011|newspaper=[[XLR8R]]|date=4 June 2009}}</ref>\n\nThe Glitch Mob's first album ''[[Drink the Sea]]'' peaked at number 57 on the [[CMJ]] Top 200 Chart for College Radio.<ref>{{cite web|author=Nonagon|url=http://www.controllerism.com/the-glitch-mobs-music-aids-disaster-relief|title=The Glitch Mob\u2019s music aids disaster relief|work=[[Controllerism]]|date=8 November 2011}}</ref> The album's debut led [[Electronic Musician]] to run a cover story on the trio.<ref name=eMusician>{{cite web|last=Levine|first=Mike|title=The Glitch Mob {{!}} Controller Freaks|url=http://emusician.com/interviews/feature/glitch_mob_controller_freaks/|work=eMusician|publisher=Penton Media, Inc.|date=16 June 2010|accessdate=23 February 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100823033643/http://emusician.com/interviews/feature/glitch_mob_controller_freaks/|archivedate=23 August 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Their single \"Drive It Like You Stole It\" was number 2 on [[XLR8R]]'s Top Downloads of 2010 list.<ref>{{cite web|last=Taylor|first=Ken|title=Grab XLR8R's Top Downloads of 2010|url=http://www.xlr8r.com/features/2010/12/grab-xlr8rs-top-downloads-2010-p|work=XLR8R|date=10 December 2010|accessdate=23 February 2011}}</ref> Their single \"Warrior Concerto\" was used in the official trailer for ''[[The Crew (video game)|The Crew]]''. The sophomore Glitch Mob album ''[[Love Death Immortality]]'' debuted at number 1 on the Billboard [[Dance/Electronic Songs]] chart<ref>{{cite web|last=Murray|first=Gordon|title=Glitch Mob Grabs Top Spot On Dance/Electronic Albums Chart|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/code/5915613/glitch-mob-grabs-top-spot-on-danceelectronic-albums-chart|work=Billboard|date=21 February 2014|accessdate=15 April 2014}}</ref> and at number 13 on the Billboard 200.<ref>{{cite web|title=Billboard 200 Chart History for The Glitch Mob 'Love Death Immortality'|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/the-glitch-mob/chart-history/independent-albums/song/814979|work=Billboard|accessdate=12 October 2018}}</ref> Their remix for \"[[Seven Nation Army]]\" by [[The White Stripes]] was featured in the trailer for the 2013 film [[G.I. Joe: Retaliation]], as well as the trailer for the [[World War I]] [[first-person shooter]], ''[[Battlefield 1]]''.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4F0LKs4sYFo Battlefield 1 trailer music]</ref> Their song \"Skullclub\" was featured in an advert for [[Amazon Echo]].<ref>[https://www.ispot.tv/ad/7Uir/amazon-echo-controlled-by-your-voice-song-by-the-glitch-mob Alexa Commercial at ispot.tv]</ref>\n\n==Touring==\nDuring their 2014 tour The Glitch Mob performed with a new musical element they called \"The Blade.\" Built by movie set designers, it is a customized, painted set piece that houses both lights and instruments.<ref name=\"KastritisInterview\">{{cite web |last1=Kastritis |first1=Thanasi |title=Interview: Josh Mayer of The Glitch Mob |url=http://soundofboston.com/interview-josh-mayer-of-the-glitch-mob/ |website=Sound of Boston |accessdate=29 October 2014}}</ref> In an interview with [http://www.soundofboston.com Sound of Boston] Josh Mayer explained, \"It really represents who we are and what we\u2019re trying to say, and it\u2019s just a functional thing that lets us play our music the way we want to play our music.\"<ref name=\"KastritisInterview\" />\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Albums===\n* ''[[Drink the Sea]]'' (2010)\n* ''[[Drink the Sea - The Remixes]]'' (2011)\n* ''[[Love Death Immortality]]'' (2014) \n* ''Love Death Immortality Remixes'' (2015)\n* ''See Without Eyes'' (2018)\n\n===Extended plays===\n*''We Can Make the World Stop'' (2011)\n*''Piece of the Indestructible'' (2015)\n*''Chemicals'' (2020)<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://dancingastronaut.com/2020/03/the-glitch-mob-deliver-chemicals-ep-their-first-new-music-since-2018-stream/ |title=The Glitch Mob deliver ''Chemicals'' EP [Stream] |last=Levin |first=Harry |date=21 March 2020 |website=Dancing Astronaut |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325073700/https://dancingastronaut.com/2020/03/the-glitch-mob-deliver-chemicals-ep-their-first-new-music-since-2018-stream/ |archive-date=25 March 2020 |accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Singles===\n* \"Episode 8\" (featuring D-Styles) (2009)\n* \"Black Aura\" (featuring Theophilus London) (2009)\n* \"Beyond Monday\" (2010)\n* \"Drive It Like You Stole It\" (2010)\n* \"Warrior Concerto\" (2011)\n* \"We Can Make the World Stop\" (2011)\n* \"Can't Kill Us\" (2013)\n* \"Better Hide, Better Run\" (featuring Mark Johns) (2015)\n* \"How Could This Be Wrong\" (featuring Tula) (2018)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.edmsauce.com/2018/02/22/glitch-mob-release-atmospheric-first-single-off-upcoming-album/ |title=The Glitch Mob Release Atmospheric First Single Off of Upcoming Album |website=EDMSauce |accessdate=2018-02-23 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180223073748/https://www.edmsauce.com/2018/02/22/glitch-mob-release-atmospheric-first-single-off-upcoming-album/ |archivedate=2018-02-23}}</ref>\n* \"Take Me With You\" (featuring Arama) (2018)\n* \"I Could Be Anything\" (featuring Elohim) (2018)<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://mixmag.net/read/the-glitch-mob-reveal-a-lustrous-music-video-for-i-could-be-anything-news |title=The Glitch Mob Reveal a Lustrous Music Video for \u2018I Could Be Anything\u2019 |last=Holbrook |first=Cameron |date=2018-04-06 |website=Mixmag |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180407053117/http://mixmag.net/read/the-glitch-mob-reveal-a-lustrous-music-video-for-i-could-be-anything-news |archive-date=2018-04-07 |accessdate=2018-04-07}}</ref>\n* \"Go Light\" (2018)\n* \"Rise\" (featuring [[Mako (DJ)|Mako]] and [[The Word Alive]]) (2018)<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youredm.com/2018/09/26/the-glitch-mob-mako-and-the-word-alive-create-new-song-for-league-of-legends-worlds-2018/ |title=The Glitch Mob, Mako, and the Word Alive Create New Song for League of Legends Worlds 2018 |last=Meadow |first=Matthew |date=2018-09-26 |website=Your EDM |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180926205126/https://www.youredm.com/2018/09/26/the-glitch-mob-mako-and-the-word-alive-create-new-song-for-league-of-legends-worlds-2018/ |archive-date=2018-09-26 |accessdate=2018-09-27}}</ref>\n* \"System Bleed\" (with Lick) (2019)<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youredm.com/2019/10/05/the-glitch-mob-lick-team-up-for-epic-bass-monster-system-bleed/ |title=The Glitch Mob & LICK team up for epic bass monster 'System Bleed' |last=Meadow |first=Matthew |date=2019-10-05 |website=Your EDM |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191006053049/https://www.youredm.com/2019/10/05/the-glitch-mob-lick-team-up-for-epic-bass-monster-system-bleed/ |archive-date=2019-10-06 |accessdate=2019-10-11}}</ref>\n* \"Lazer Vision\" (with Zeke Beats) (2019)<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://dancingastronaut.com/2019/10/glitch-mob-and-zeke-beats-team-up-for-lazer-vision/ |title=Glitch Mob and ZEKE BEATS team up for 'Lazer Vision' |author=Dancing Astronaut staff |date=2019-10-27 |website=Dancing Astronaut |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191105004641/https://dancingastronaut.com/2019/10/glitch-mob-and-zeke-beats-team-up-for-lazer-vision/ |archive-date=2019-11-09 |access-date=2019-11-09}}</ref>\n* \"Momentary Lapse\" (with [[1788-L]]) (2019)<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youredm.com/2019/11/08/the-glitch-mob-teams-with-1788-l-for-new-collaboration-momentary-lapse/ |title=The Glitch Mob teams with 1788-L for new collaboration, 'Momentary Lapse' |last=Meadow |first=Matthew |date=2019-11-08 |website=Your EDM |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191109073826/https://www.youredm.com/2019/11/08/the-glitch-mob-teams-with-1788-l-for-new-collaboration-momentary-lapse/ |archive-date=2019-11-09 |accessdate=2019-11-09}}</ref>\n\n===Mixtapes===\n* ''Crush Mode'' (2008)\n* ''Local Area Network'' (2009)\n* ''Drink the Sea Part II: The Mixtape'' (2010)\n* ''More Voltage'' (2011)\n* ''Do Lab Mix 2016'' (2016)\n\n===Remixes===\n* Matty G \u2013 \"West Coast Rocks\" (2008)\n* [[Evil Nine]] \u2013 \"All the Cash\" (2008)\n* [[Coheed and Cambria]] \u2013 \"Feathers\" (2008)\n* [[Sound Tribe Sector 9|STS9]] \u2013 \"Beyond Right Now\" (2008)\n* [[TV on the Radio]] \u2013 \"Red Dress\" (2009)\n* Nalepa \u2013 \"Monday\" (2009)\n* [[Linkin Park]] \u2013 \"[[Waiting for the End (Linkin Park song)|Waiting for the End]]\" (2010)\n* [[Krazy Baldhead]] \u2013 \"The 4th Movement\" (2010)\n* [[Daft Punk]] \u2013 \"[[Derezzed]]\" (2011)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/ca/album/tron-legacy-reconfigured/426251101|title=TRON: Legacy Reconfigured on Itunes}}</ref>\n* [[The White Stripes]] \u2013 \"[[Seven Nation Army]]\" (2011)\n* [[Bassnectar]] \u2013 \"Heads Up\" (2012)\n* [[The Prodigy]] \u2013 \"[[Breathe (The Prodigy song)|Breathe]]\" (2012)\n* [[Metallica]] \u2013 \"[[Lords of Summer]]\" (2015)\n* [[Illenium]] \u2013 \"[[Crawl Outta Love]]\" (2018)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.edmsauce.com/2018/03/01/glitch-mob-drops-unbelievable-remix-illeniums-crawl-outta-love/ |title=The Glitch Mob Drops Unbelievable Remix of Illenium\u2019s 'Crawl Outta Love' |website=EDMSauce |accessdate=2018-03-02}}</ref>\n* [[Odesza]] featuring Sasha Sloan \u2013 \"Falls\" (2018)<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://dancingastronaut.com/2018/10/odeszas-falls-gets-star-remix-pack-kaskade-tokimonsta/ |title=Odesza's \u201cFalls\u201d gets an all-star remix pack from Kaskade, TOKiMONSTA, and more |last=Norris |first=Asher |date=2018-10-21 |website=[[Dancing Astronaut]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181022053321/https://dancingastronaut.com/2018/10/odeszas-falls-gets-star-remix-pack-kaskade-tokimonsta/ |archive-date=2018-10-22 |accessdate=2018-10-22}}</ref>\n\n===Music videos===\n* \"Beyond Monday\" (2010)\n* \"Between Two Points\" (2011)\n* \"We Can Make the World Stop\" (2011)\n* \"Can't Kill Us\" (2013)\n* \"How Could This Be Wrong (feat. Tula)\" (2018)\n* \u201cTake Me With You (feat. Arama)\u201d (2018)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website}}\n* [http://glassairrecords.com Glass Air Records]\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2011}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Glitch Mob}}\n[[Category:American electronic musicians]]\n[[Category:Intelligent dance musicians]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 2006]]\n[[Category:2006 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:Ableton Live users]]\n[[Category:Musical groups from Los Angeles]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name             = The Glitch Mob\n| image            = The Glitch Mob 2014.jpg\n| caption          = The Glitch Mob performing in 2014\n| landscape        = yes\n| background       = group_or_band\n| origin           = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], United States\n| genre            = {{flatlist|\n* [[Glitch (music)|Glitch]] \n* [[electronica]] \n* [[Intelligent dance music|IDM]]\n*[[Industrial music|industrial]]\n}}\n| years_active     = 2006\u2013present\n| label            = Glass Air Records\n| website          = {{URL|theglitchmob.com}}\n| current_members  = [[edIT (musician)|edIT]] (Edward Ma)<br/>Boreta (Justin Boreta)<br/>Ooah (Josh Mayer)\n| past_members     = Kraddy (Matthew Kratz)<br/>Kitty-D (David Altamira)\n}}\n\n'''The Glitch Mob''' is an American [[electronic music]] group from [[Los Angeles]], [[California]]. It consists of [[Edit (musician)|edIT]] (Edward Ma), [[Boreta]] (Justin Boreta) and [[Ooah]] (Josh Mayer). Chris Martins of ''[[LA Weekly]]'' noted that they \"have undoubtedly found the largest audience of any L.A. beat scene artist yet.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Martins|first=Chris|title=Beat Music Goes Big Time: Glitch Mob & Fighting Gravity Make Semi-Finals on America's Got Talent|url=http://blogs.laweekly.com/westcoastsound/2010/09/glitch_mob_fighting_gravity_americas_got_talent.php|accessdate=23 February 2011|newspaper=[[LA Weekly]]|date=1 September 2010}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe Glitch Mob, originally a four-piece including [[Kraddy]], was formed within the burgeoning Los Angeles bass-driven 'beat' scene. The group made a name for themselves playing live, choosing to perform with laptops and MIDI controllers like the [[Lemur Input Device|Lemur]].<ref name=Sea>{{cite news|last=Brown|first=August|title=The Glitch Mob swims in a vast, ominous 'Sea'|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/music_blog/2010/06/the-glitch-mob-swims-in-a-vast-ominous-sea.html|accessdate=23 February 2011|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=11 June 2010}}</ref><ref name=CDM>{{cite web|last=Kirn|first=Peter|title=The Glitch Mob: Tour, Free Single Download, Multiple Laptops + Lemurs|url=http://createdigitalmusic.com/2010/03/the-glitch-mob-tour-free-single-download-multiple-laptops-lemurs/|work=Create Digital Music|date=25 March 2010|accessdate=23 February 2011}}</ref> They won fans through showcasing their chosen technology during solo performances, and after gaining attention in Los Angeles and San Francisco, the group eventually toured more widely along the West Coast and then to various festivals worldwide.<ref name=URB>{{cite web|last=Levine|first=Noah|title=Live Review: The Glitch Mob @ Double Door (05.01.10)|url=http://www.urb.com/2010/05/03/live-review-the-glitch-mob-double-door-05-01-10/|work=[[URB (magazine)|URB]]|date=3 May 2010|accessdate=23 February 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100924152233/http://www.urb.com/2010/05/03/live-review-the-glitch-mob-double-door-05-01-10/|archivedate=24 September 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref> After citing \"creative differences,\" founding member Kraddy left the group in 2009.<ref name=XLR8R>{{cite news|last=Marston|first=Jennifer|title=Kraddy Departs from The Glitch Mob|url=https://www.xlr8r.com/news/2009/06/kraddy-departs-from-the-glitch-mob|accessdate=23 February 2011|newspaper=[[XLR8R]]|date=4 June 2009}}</ref>\n\nThe Glitch Mob's first album ''[[Drink the Sea]]'' peaked at number 57 on the [[CMJ]] Top 200 Chart for College Radio.<ref>{{cite web|author=Nonagon|url=http://www.controllerism.com/the-glitch-mobs-music-aids-disaster-relief|title=The Glitch Mob\u2019s music aids disaster relief|work=[[Controllerism]]|date=8 November 2011}}</ref> The album's debut led [[Electronic Musician]] to run a cover story on the trio.<ref name=eMusician>{{cite web|last=Levine|first=Mike|title=The Glitch Mob {{!}} Controller Freaks|url=http://emusician.com/interviews/feature/glitch_mob_controller_freaks/|work=eMusician|publisher=Penton Media, Inc.|date=16 June 2010|accessdate=23 February 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100823033643/http://emusician.com/interviews/feature/glitch_mob_controller_freaks/|archivedate=23 August 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Their single \"Drive It Like You Stole It\" was number 2 on [[XLR8R]]'s Top Downloads of 2010 list.<ref>{{cite web|last=Taylor|first=Ken|title=Grab XLR8R's Top Downloads of 2010|url=http://www.xlr8r.com/features/2010/12/grab-xlr8rs-top-downloads-2010-p|work=XLR8R|date=10 December 2010|accessdate=23 February 2011}}</ref> Their single \"Warrior Concerto\" was used in the official trailer for ''[[The Crew (video game)|The Crew]]''. The sophomore Glitch Mob album ''[[Love Death Immortality]]'' debuted at number 1 on the Billboard [[Dance/Electronic Songs]] chart<ref>{{cite web|last=Murray|first=Gordon|title=Glitch Mob Grabs Top Spot On Dance/Electronic Albums Chart|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/code/5915613/glitch-mob-grabs-top-spot-on-danceelectronic-albums-chart|work=Billboard|date=21 February 2014|accessdate=15 April 2014}}</ref> and at number 13 on the Billboard 200<ref>{{cite web|title=Billboard 200 Chart History for The Glitch Mob 'Love Death Immortality'|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/the-glitch-mob/chart-history/independent-albums/song/814979|work=Billboard|accessdate=12 October 2018}}</ref>. Their remix for \"[[Seven Nation Army]]\" by [[The White Stripes]] was featured in the trailer for the 2013 film [[G.I. Joe: Retaliation]], as well as the trailer for the [[World War I]] [[first-person shooter]], ''[[Battlefield 1]]''.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4F0LKs4sYFo Battlefield 1 trailer music]</ref> Their song \"Skullclub\" was featured in an advert for [[Amazon Echo]].<ref>[https://www.ispot.tv/ad/7Uir/amazon-echo-controlled-by-your-voice-song-by-the-glitch-mob Alexa Commercial at ispot.tv]</ref>\n\n==Touring==\nDuring their 2014 tour The Glitch Mob performed with a new musical element they called \"The Blade.\" Built by movie set designers, it is a customized, painted set piece that houses both lights and instruments.<ref name=\"KastritisInterview\">{{cite web |last1=Kastritis |first1=Thanasi |title=Interview: Josh Mayer of The Glitch Mob |url=http://soundofboston.com/interview-josh-mayer-of-the-glitch-mob/ |website=Sound of Boston |accessdate=29 October 2014}}</ref> In an interview with [http://www.soundofboston.com Sound of Boston] Josh Mayer explained, \"It really represents who we are and what we\u2019re trying to say, and it\u2019s just a functional thing that lets us play our music the way we want to play our music.\"<ref name=\"KastritisInterview\" />\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Albums===\n* ''[[Drink the Sea]]'' (2010)\n* ''[[Drink the Sea - The Remixes]]'' (2011)\n* ''[[Love Death Immortality]]'' (2014) \n* ''Love Death Immortality Remixes'' (2015)\n* ''See Without Eyes'' (2018)\n\n===Extended plays===\n*''We Can Make the World Stop'' (2011)\n*''Piece of the Indestructible'' (2015)\n*''Chemicals'' (2020)<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://dancingastronaut.com/2020/03/the-glitch-mob-deliver-chemicals-ep-their-first-new-music-since-2018-stream/ |title=The Glitch Mob deliver ''Chemicals'' EP [Stream] |last=Levin |first=Harry |date=21 March 2020 |website=Dancing Astronaut |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325073700/https://dancingastronaut.com/2020/03/the-glitch-mob-deliver-chemicals-ep-their-first-new-music-since-2018-stream/ |archive-date=25 March 2020 |accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Singles===\n* \"Episode 8\" (featuring D-Styles) (2009)\n* \"Black Aura\" (featuring Theophilus London) (2009)\n* \"Beyond Monday\" (2010)\n* \"Drive It Like You Stole It\" (2010)\n* \"Warrior Concerto\" (2011)\n* \"We Can Make the World Stop\" (2011)\n* \"Can't Kill Us\" (2013)\n* \"Better Hide, Better Run\" (featuring Mark Johns) (2015)\n* \"How Could This Be Wrong\" (featuring Tula) (2018)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.edmsauce.com/2018/02/22/glitch-mob-release-atmospheric-first-single-off-upcoming-album/ |title=The Glitch Mob Release Atmospheric First Single Off of Upcoming Album |website=EDMSauce |accessdate=2018-02-23 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180223073748/https://www.edmsauce.com/2018/02/22/glitch-mob-release-atmospheric-first-single-off-upcoming-album/ |archivedate=2018-02-23}}</ref>\n* \"Take Me With You\" (featuring Arama) (2018)\n* \"I Could Be Anything\" (featuring Elohim) (2018)<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://mixmag.net/read/the-glitch-mob-reveal-a-lustrous-music-video-for-i-could-be-anything-news |title=The Glitch Mob Reveal a Lustrous Music Video for \u2018I Could Be Anything\u2019 |last=Holbrook |first=Cameron |date=2018-04-06 |website=Mixmag |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180407053117/http://mixmag.net/read/the-glitch-mob-reveal-a-lustrous-music-video-for-i-could-be-anything-news |archive-date=2018-04-07 |accessdate=2018-04-07}}</ref>\n* \"Go Light\" (2018)\n* \"Rise\" (featuring [[Mako (DJ)|Mako]] and [[The Word Alive]]) (2018)<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youredm.com/2018/09/26/the-glitch-mob-mako-and-the-word-alive-create-new-song-for-league-of-legends-worlds-2018/ |title=The Glitch Mob, Mako, and the Word Alive Create New Song for League of Legends Worlds 2018 |last=Meadow |first=Matthew |date=2018-09-26 |website=Your EDM |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180926205126/https://www.youredm.com/2018/09/26/the-glitch-mob-mako-and-the-word-alive-create-new-song-for-league-of-legends-worlds-2018/ |archive-date=2018-09-26 |accessdate=2018-09-27}}</ref>\n* \"System Bleed\" (with Lick) (2019)<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youredm.com/2019/10/05/the-glitch-mob-lick-team-up-for-epic-bass-monster-system-bleed/ |title=The Glitch Mob & LICK team up for epic bass monster 'System Bleed' |last=Meadow |first=Matthew |date=2019-10-05 |website=Your EDM |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191006053049/https://www.youredm.com/2019/10/05/the-glitch-mob-lick-team-up-for-epic-bass-monster-system-bleed/ |archive-date=2019-10-06 |accessdate=2019-10-11}}</ref>\n* \"Lazer Vision\" (with Zeke Beats) (2019)<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://dancingastronaut.com/2019/10/glitch-mob-and-zeke-beats-team-up-for-lazer-vision/ |title=Glitch Mob and ZEKE BEATS team up for 'Lazer Vision' |author=Dancing Astronaut staff |date=2019-10-27 |website=Dancing Astronaut |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191105004641/https://dancingastronaut.com/2019/10/glitch-mob-and-zeke-beats-team-up-for-lazer-vision/ |archive-date=2019-11-09 |access-date=2019-11-09}}</ref>\n* \"Momentary Lapse\" (with [[1788-L]]) (2019)<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youredm.com/2019/11/08/the-glitch-mob-teams-with-1788-l-for-new-collaboration-momentary-lapse/ |title=The Glitch Mob teams with 1788-L for new collaboration, 'Momentary Lapse' |last=Meadow |first=Matthew |date=2019-11-08 |website=Your EDM |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191109073826/https://www.youredm.com/2019/11/08/the-glitch-mob-teams-with-1788-l-for-new-collaboration-momentary-lapse/ |archive-date=2019-11-09 |accessdate=2019-11-09}}</ref>\n\n===Mixtapes===\n* ''Crush Mode'' (2008)\n* ''Local Area Network'' (2009)\n* ''Drink the Sea Part II: The Mixtape'' (2010)\n* ''More Voltage'' (2011)\n* ''Do Lab Mix 2016'' (2016)\n\n===Remixes===\n* Matty G \u2013 \"West Coast Rocks\" (2008)\n* [[Evil Nine]] \u2013 \"All the Cash\" (2008)\n* [[Coheed and Cambria]] \u2013 \"Feathers\" (2008)\n* [[Sound Tribe Sector 9|STS9]] \u2013 \"Beyond Right Now\" (2008)\n* [[TV on the Radio]] \u2013 \"Red Dress\" (2009)\n* Nalepa \u2013 \"Monday\" (2009)\n* [[Linkin Park]] \u2013 \"[[Waiting for the End (Linkin Park song)|Waiting for the End]]\" (2010)\n* [[Krazy Baldhead]] \u2013 \"The 4th Movement\" (2010)\n* [[Daft Punk]] \u2013 \"[[Derezzed]]\" (2011)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/ca/album/tron-legacy-reconfigured/426251101|title=TRON: Legacy Reconfigured on Itunes}}</ref>\n* [[The White Stripes]] \u2013 \"[[Seven Nation Army]]\" (2011)\n* [[Bassnectar]] \u2013 \"Heads Up\" (2012)\n* [[The Prodigy]] \u2013 \"[[Breathe (The Prodigy song)|Breathe]]\" (2012)\n* [[Metallica]] \u2013 \"[[Lords of Summer]]\" (2015)\n* [[Illenium]] \u2013 \"[[Crawl Outta Love]]\" (2018)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.edmsauce.com/2018/03/01/glitch-mob-drops-unbelievable-remix-illeniums-crawl-outta-love/ |title=The Glitch Mob Drops Unbelievable Remix of Illenium\u2019s 'Crawl Outta Love' |website=EDMSauce |accessdate=2018-03-02}}</ref>\n* [[Odesza]] featuring Sasha Sloan \u2013 \"Falls\" (2018)<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://dancingastronaut.com/2018/10/odeszas-falls-gets-star-remix-pack-kaskade-tokimonsta/ |title=Odesza's \u201cFalls\u201d gets an all-star remix pack from Kaskade, TOKiMONSTA, and more |last=Norris |first=Asher |date=2018-10-21 |website=[[Dancing Astronaut]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181022053321/https://dancingastronaut.com/2018/10/odeszas-falls-gets-star-remix-pack-kaskade-tokimonsta/ |archive-date=2018-10-22 |accessdate=2018-10-22}}</ref>\n\n===Music videos===\n* \"Beyond Monday\" (2010)\n* \"Between Two Points\" (2011)\n* \"We Can Make the World Stop\" (2011)\n* \"Can't Kill Us\" (2013)\n* \"How Could This Be Wrong (feat. Tula)\" (2018)\n* \u201cTake Me With You (feat. Arama)\u201d (2018)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website}}\n* [http://glassairrecords.com Glass Air Records]\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2011}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Glitch Mob}}\n[[Category:American electronic musicians]]\n[[Category:Intelligent dance musicians]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 2006]]\n[[Category:2006 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:Ableton Live users]]\n[[Category:Musical groups from Los Angeles]]\n", "name_user": "DannyS712", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing the location of periods / full stops", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Glitch_Mob"}
{"title_page": "Thoroughbred racing in New Zealand", "text_new": "The '''[[horse racing|racing]] of [[Thoroughbred]] horses''' or gallopers as they are also known is a popular sport in [[New Zealand]]. \n\nThe governing body is New Zealand Thoroughbred Racing Incorporated. \n\n[[Image:The Winner by 3 quarters of a length - Cluden Creek.jpg|thumb|right|300px|[[Wellington Cup]] race in [[New Zealand]] ]]\n\n==History==\n\nThe first [[totalisator]] machine in the world was installed at [[Ellerslie Racecourse]] in 1913, see Sir [[George Julius]]).\n\nFamous New Zealand racehorses include the great mares [[Desert Gold (horse)|Desert Gold]], [[Cuddle (horse)|Cuddle]], [[Horlicks (horse)|Horlicks]] and [[Sunline]], plus [[Carbine (horse)|Carbine]], [[Kindergarten (horse)|Kindergarten]], [[Phar Lap]], [[Nightmarch]], [[Gloaming (horse)|Gloaming]], [[Rising Fast]], [[Il Tempo (horse)|Il Tempo]], [[Advance (horse)|Advance]], [[Tulloch (horse)|Tulloch]] and [[Grey Way]]. Both Australia and New Zealand claim Phar Lap. Gloaming, an Australian-bred horse, raced in Australia and in New Zealand.\n\n===Women jockeys===\nIn 1977 the New Zealand Racing Conference accepted female jockeys and they became eligible to ride on 15 July 1978. Previously Linda Jones was the first to apply for an apprentice\u2019s licence and be turned down. She had ridden in a number of lady riders events over many years in New Zealand and overseas such as in Brazil, which highlighted that New Zealand and Australia were outliers in not allowing women to compete with male jockeys in professional races. \n\nThe first win by a woman in New Zealand was visiting Canadian jockey Joan Phipps, at Te Awamutu in November 1977. Sue Day from Christchurch became the first New Zealand female jockey winner in a totalisator race against males on 22 July 1978 when she won with the Ned Thistoll-trained Jaws in the Waybrook Handicap at Timaru.<ref>https://www.horsetalk.co.nz/2018/07/13/sue-historic-day-40-years-racing-milestone/</ref> Other female riders then included [[Jo Giles |Joanne Hale]], Vivienne Kaye, Joanne Lamond and Cherie Saxon.<ref>https://www.nzherald.co.nz/sport/news/article.cfm?c_id=4&objectid=3541362</ref> \n\nLinda Jones\u2019 first win was on Big Bickies at Te Rapa and soon after Royal Petite was the first Open Handicap winner for a female jockey. Subsequent highlight wins for Linda were Lovaro in the Queen Elizabeth Handicap and Holy Toledo in the Wellington Derby (possibly the first female jockey world-wide to win a Derby).  Linda Jones was also the first female jockey to win a professional race against males at a registered meeting in Australia (Doomben).<ref>https://www.nzherald.co.nz/sport/news/article.cfm?c_id=4&objectid=12088993</ref>\n\nFemale riders have subsequently gone on to win the New Zealand premiership; Lisa Cropp (2005-2007), Lisa Allpress (2012, 2016 and 2019) and Samantha Collett (2018).\n\nIn late February 2020 Lisa Allpress was the first female to win a thoroughbred race in Saudi Arabia on the horse Matmon at King Abdullah Aziz racetrack in Riyadh.<ref>https://www.bloodhorse.com/horse-racing/articles/238767/jockey-lisa-allpress-makes-history-in-saudi-arabia</ref> She was competing in the inaugural International jockeys challenge in which she competed with 14 other jockeys including 7 women. The challenge was won by American Hall of Fame jockey Mike Smith, Swiss-born Germany based Sibylle Vogt was second while Lisa was third equal with French jockey Mickaelle Michel.<ref>https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/racing/119949865/lisa-allpress-becomes-first-female-jockey-to-ride-a-winner-in-saudi-arabia</ref>\n\n===New Zealand horses in Australia===\n\nHorses frequently move between New Zealand and its neighbour [[Australia]], for races and for [[Horse breeding|breeding]] purposes. \n\nBetween 1882 and {{as of | 2019 | alt = 2019}} New Zealand-bred horses won Australia's [[Melbourne Cup]] 43 times.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!-- no byline --> |title=Melbourne Cup 2019 full guide: Kiwi connections, prizemoney, livestream |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/racing/117158773/melbourne-cup-2019-full-guide-kiwi-connections-prizemoney-livestream |accessdate=25 January 2020 |work=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]] |date=November 5, 2019 }}</ref> During the 2008-09 racing season 19 New Zealand-bred Thoroughbreds won 22 [[Group One]] races around the world.<ref>\nRacetrack Sires 2009, June/August, 2009, ''Record season for the New Zealand breed'', p.52\n</ref>\n\n==Race clubs and courses of New Zealand==\n\nThoroughbred racing is held throughout New Zealand, including courses in some of the smaller centres.\n\n{| class = \"wikitable sortable\" | border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\"; style=\"border-collapse:collapse; font-size:100%;\"\n|- bgcolor=\"LightSteelBlue\" align=\"center\"\n! width=\"100px\" | '''Club'''<br />\n! width=\"170px\" | '''Course, Town/city/province'''  <br />\n! width=\"30px\" | '''Track'''\n! width=\"30px\" | '''Direction'''\n! width=\"30px\" | '''Straight'''\n! width=\"150px\" | '''Notes'''  <br />\n|-\n| Ashburton RC     || [[Ashburton, New Zealand]]  || 1876m ||left-handed || 382m ||\n|-\n| Auckland RC   || [[Ellerslie Racecourse]], Auckland  ||  1876m ||right-handed ||382m||\n|-\n| Avondale JC   || [[Avondale, Auckland]] ||  1800m ||right-handed|| 450m ||\n|-\n| Banks Peninsula RC|| Motukarara, Canterbury  ||  1800m ||left-handed  ||400m||\n|-\n| Beaumont RC    || Wingatui, Dunedin (since 1987) || 2000m|| left-handed ||350m || Part of Gallop South \n|-\n| Cambridge RC     || Te Rapa, Hamilton || 1800m || left-handed || 420m|| Owns training course/complex at Cambridge\n|-\n| Canterbury JC    || [[Riccarton Park Racecourse | Riccarton Park]], Christchurch  || 2400m || left-handed ||400m||\n|-\n| Central Otago RC    || Omakau  || 1600m ||left-handed|| 300m|| Part of Gallop South \n|-\n| Counties RC    || Pukekohe Park, Franklin  ||1900m ||right-handed ||520m ||\n|-\n| Dargaville RC    || Awakino Point   ||1600m ||left-handed || 