{"title_page": "Wojciech Jagielski", "text_new": "[[File:Wojciech Jagielski (publicysta) 3842.jpg|thumb|200px|Wojciech Jagielski]]\n'''Wojciech Jagielski''' (born 12 September 1960<ref>[http://www.polishculture-nyc.org/?itemcategory=30817&personDetailId=675 Polish cultural institute New York]</ref>) is a [[Poles|Polish]] journalist and correspondent.<ref name=\"H1000202356\">[http://ic.galegroup.com/ic/bic1/ReferenceDetailsPage/ReferenceDetailsWindow?failOverType=&query=&prodId=BIC1&windowstate=normal&contentModules=&mode=view&displayGroupName=Reference&limiter=&currPage=&disableHighlighting=false&displayGroups=&sortBy=&search_within_results=&p=BIC1&action=e&catId=&activityType=&scanId=&documentId=GALE%7CH1000202356&source=Bookmark&u=22396_largo&jsid=d6a9b417c3ca239fc33e36fc38c0cd60 \"Wojciech Jagielski.\" Contemporary Authors Online. Detroit: Gale, 2011. Biography in Context. Web. 7 Jan. 2014. Gale Document Number: GALE|H1000202356]</ref> He has won acclaim for his reports on journeys to the world's worst trouble spots. From 1991 to 2012, he worked for a leading Polish newspaper, ''[[Gazeta Wyborcza]]'' (Electoral Gazette), was a [[BBC]] correspondent,<ref name=\"H1000202356\" /> and occasional contributor to ''[[Le Monde]]''.<ref name=\"H1000202356\" /> He reported mainly from conflict zones in the [[Transcaucasus]], the [[Caucasus]], [[Central Asia]] and [[Africa]].<ref name=\"H1000202356\" /> His writing continues the tradition of reportage of [[Ryszard Kapuscinski]], Jagielski's mentor and friend.<ref>''The Bible of Journalism'', 2010, edited by Andrzej Skworz, Andrzej Nizio\u0142ek</ref><ref>[http://www.bookinstitute.pl/en,ik,site,40,78,1616.php Book Institute Poland]</ref>\n\n== Life ==\n\nJagielski graduated from a Warsaw high school named after Wladyslaw IV. He earned a degree from the Faculty of Political Science at [[Warsaw University]]. He studied political science, but when the declaration of [[martial law in Poland]] in 1981 introduced the obligation to attend all classes, he chose individual programs and took up African studies.\n\nAfter graduation he briefly worked in television, then from December 1986 for the [[Polish Press Agency]].<ref name=\"H1000202356\" /> He wanted to report on Africa, but the station managers were not too interested in this topic. From then, he decided that the Caucasus would become his second specialization. In 1991 he moved to the ''[[Gazeta Wyborcza]]'', for which he wrote until the end of March 2012. He has also published several well-received books. He lives in Zalesie near Warsaw.<ref>[http://wyborcza.pl/dziennikarze/0,84009.html Journalist: Wojciech Jagielski], ''Gazeta Wyborcza''</ref>\n\n== Books ==\n\nIn 2004 he published a book, ''A Good Place to Die'' (Dobre miejsce do umierania),<ref name=\"H1000202356\" /> about his years travelling through the Caucasus and Transcaucasian regions during the fall of the [[Soviet imperialism|Soviet Empire]] and the creation of new independent countries.<ref>[http://www.bookinstitute.pl/en,ik,site,40,80,436.php ''A good place to die''], Book Institute Poland</ref>\n\nPublished in 2002, ''Pray for the Rain'' (Modlitwa o deszcz),<ref name=\"H1000202356\" /> about Afghanistan, was nominated for the NIKE Award 2003, and received an Amber Butterfly in the Arkady Fiedler Competition and the J\u00f3zef Tischner Award. It was the result of eleven trips to Afghanistan, which took place between spring 1992 and the autumn of 2001. The book is a chronicle of the rise and fall of regimes in Afghanistan and a description of the bloody and fratricidal wars. The main subjects of the book are such well-known figures as [[Osama bin Laden]], [[Ahmad Shah Massoud]], [[Gulbuddin Hekmatyar]], [[Mohammed Omar|Mullah Omar]] and [[Najibullah Zazi]].<ref>[http://culture.pl/en/work/praying-for-rain-wojciech-jagielski Review: ''Praying for Rain'', Culture.pl, managed by Adam Mickiewicz Institute]</ref>\n\nHis book ''Towers of Stone: The Battle of Wills in Chechnya'',<ref name=\"H1000202356\" /> won the Italian [[Literatura Frontera Award]] in 2009 and was published in English by [[Seven Stories Press]].<ref name=\"H1000202356\" /><ref>{{cite book|last=Jagielski|first=Wojciech|year=2009|title=Towers of Stone|publisher=[[Seven Stories Press]]|isbn=978-1-58322-900-2|ref=harv|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/towersofstonebat00jagi}}</ref> Jagielski presents the bitter story of war in [[Chechnya]], and the conflict between groups of warriors with their leaders: [[Shamil Basayev]] and [[Aslan Maskhadov]], against the powerful Russian army.<ref>[http://www.economist.com/node/15063856 \"A small corner, very bloody\"], ''The Economist''</ref>\n\nHis next book, ''The Night Wanderers: Uganda's Children and the Lord's Resistance Army'', about [[child soldier]]s in Uganda, discusses God's Army leader [[Joseph Kony]], who claims that he was possessed by spirits, and former tyrant [[Idi Amin]], who had styled himself as the \"lord of all beings.\"<ref>[http://washingtonpeacecenter.net/node/7496 Washington Peace Center]</ref><ref>[http://culture.pl/en/event/a-reporters-perspective-on-war-jagielskis-night-wanderers-in-the-us \"A Reporter's Perspective on War: Jagielski's Night Wanderers in the US\"], ''Culture''</ref>\n\nHis most recent book to appear in English is ''Burning the Grass: At the Heart of Change in South Africa 1990-2011,'' which examines the 2010 murder of white supremacist South African leader [[Eug\u00e8ne Terre'Blanche]].<ref>[http://catalog.sevenstories.com/products/burning-the-grass-at-the-heart-of-change-in-south-africa-1990-2011]</ref>\n\n== Honors and awards==\n\n*2009: in recognition of his valuable and bold reporting of international issues, [[Rados\u0142aw Sikorski]], Minister of Foreign Affairs, awarded him with the ''[[Bene Merito]]'' honorary distinction.<ref>[http://www.msz.gov.pl/Minister,Radoslaw,Sikorski,awards,Bene,Merito,distinctions,31700.html Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the Republic of Poland]</ref>\n\n\u2022\tPolish Journalists Association (SDP) Awards (1996)\n\n\u2022\tThe Ksawery Pruszy\u0144ski Award of Polish PEN Club (1996)\n\n\u2022\tThe Warsaw Literary Premiere Award (2002)\n\n\u2022\tDariusz Fikus Award (2002)<ref name=\"H1000202356\" />\n\n\u2022\tJ\u00f3zef Tischner Award (2003)\n\n\u2022\tAmber Butterfly in Arkady Fiedler Competition (2003)\n\n\u2022\tMediaTory Student Journalist Award (2008)\n\n\u2022\tLiteratura Frontera Award (2009)<ref name=\"H1000202356\" />\n\nHe was also nominated for the Ryszard Kapu\u015bci\u0144ski Award and the Nike Award.\n\n== References ==\n*\n*[http://ic.galegroup.com/ic/bic1/MagazinesDetailsPage/MagazinesDetailsWindow?failOverType=&query=&prodId=BIC1&windowstate=normal&contentModules=&mode=view&displayGroupName=Magazines&limiter=&currPage=&disableHighlighting=false&displayGroups=&sortBy=&search_within_results=&p=BIC1&action=e&catId=&activityType=&scanId=&documentId=GALE%7CA213982994&source=Bookmark&u=22396_largo&jsid=af72a5cbc553c5c1c8546e556d52ba2d \"A small corner, very bloody; War in the Caucasus.\" ''The Economist'' 12 Dec. 2009: 83(EU). Biography in Context. Web. 7 Jan. 2014. Gale Document Number: GALE|A213982994]\n*[http://ic.galegroup.com/ic/bic1/AcademicJournalsDetailsPage/AcademicJournalsDetailsWindow?failOverType=&query=&prodId=BIC1&windowstate=normal&contentModules=&mode=view&displayGroupName=Journals&limiter=&currPage=&disableHighlighting=false&displayGroups=&sortBy=&search_within_results=&p=BIC1&action=e&catId=&activityType=&scanId=&documentId=GALE%7CA302770693&source=Bookmark&u=22396_largo&jsid=cf24b6c6dfce72547699c3dd09a2485d van de Walle, Nicolas. \"Recent books on international relations: Africa: The Night Wanderers: Uganda's Children and the Lord's Resistance Army.\" ''Foreign Affairs'' 91.5 (2012): 205. Biography in Context. Web. 7 Jan. 2014. Gale Document Number: GALE|A302770693] \n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jagielski, Wojciech}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:Polish journalists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Polish male writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Polish non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Polish male writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century journalists]]\n[[Category:21st-century journalists]]\n[[Category:21st-century Polish non-fiction writers]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Wojciech Jagielski (publicysta) 3842.jpg|thumb|200px|Wojciech Jagielski]]\n'''Wojciech Jagielski''' (born 12 September 1960<ref>[http://www.polishculture-nyc.org/?itemcategory=30817&personDetailId=675 Polish cultural institute New York]</ref>) is a [[Poles|Polish]] journalist and correspondent.<ref name=\"H1000202356\">[http://ic.galegroup.com/ic/bic1/ReferenceDetailsPage/ReferenceDetailsWindow?failOverType=&query=&prodId=BIC1&windowstate=normal&contentModules=&mode=view&displayGroupName=Reference&limiter=&currPage=&disableHighlighting=false&displayGroups=&sortBy=&search_within_results=&p=BIC1&action=e&catId=&activityType=&scanId=&documentId=GALE%7CH1000202356&source=Bookmark&u=22396_largo&jsid=d6a9b417c3ca239fc33e36fc38c0cd60 \"Wojciech Jagielski.\" Contemporary Authors Online. Detroit: Gale, 2011. Biography in Context. Web. 7 Jan. 2014. Gale Document Number: GALE|H1000202356]</ref> He has won acclaim for his reports on journeys to the world's worst trouble spots. From 1991 to 2012, he worked for a leading Polish newspaper, ''[[Gazeta Wyborcza]]'' (Electoral Gazette), was a [[BBC]] correspondent,<ref name=\"H1000202356\" /> and occasional contributor to ''[[Le Monde]]''.<ref name=\"H1000202356\" /> He reported mainly from conflict zones in the [[Transcaucasus]], the [[Caucasus]], [[Central Asia]] and [[Africa]].<ref name=\"H1000202356\" /> His writing continues the tradition of reportage of [[Ryszard Kapuscinski]], Jagielski's mentor and friend.<ref>''The Bible of Journalism'', 2010, edited by Andrzej Skworz, Andrzej Nizio\u0142ek</ref><ref>[http://www.bookinstitute.pl/en,ik,site,40,78,1616.php Book Institute Poland]</ref>\n\n== Life ==\n\nJagielski graduated from a Warsaw high school named after Wladyslaw IV. He earned a degree from the Faculty of Political Science at [[Warsaw University]]. He studied political science, but when the declaration of [[martial law in Poland]] in 1981 introduced the obligation to attend all classes, he chose individual programs and took up African studies.\n\nAfter graduation he briefly worked in television, then from December 1986 for the [[Polish Press Agency]].<ref name=\"H1000202356\" /> He wanted to report on Africa, but the station managers were not too interested in this topic. From then, he decided that the Caucasus would become his second specialization. In 1991 he moved to the ''[[Gazeta Wyborcza]]'', for which he wrote until the end of March 2012. He has also published several well-received books. He lives in Zalesie near Warsaw.<ref>[http://wyborcza.pl/dziennikarze/0,84009.html Journalist: Wojciech Jagielski], ''Gazeta Wyborcza''</ref>\n\n== Books ==\n\nIn 2004 he published a book, ''A Good Place to Die'' (Dobre miejsce do umierania),<ref name=\"H1000202356\" /> about his years travelling through the Caucasus and Transcaucasian regions during the fall of the [[Soviet imperialism|Soviet Empire]] and the creation of new independent countries.<ref>[http://www.bookinstitute.pl/en,ik,site,40,80,436.php ''A good place to die''], Book Institute Poland</ref>\n\nPublished in 2002, ''Pray for the Rain'' (Modlitwa o deszcz),<ref name=\"H1000202356\" /> about Afghanistan, was nominated for the NIKE Award 2003, and received an Amber Butterfly in the Arkady Fiedler Competition and the J\u00f3zef Tischner Award. It was the result of eleven trips to Afghanistan, which took place between spring 1992 and the autumn of 2001. The book is a chronicle of the rise and fall of regimes in Afghanistan and a description of the bloody and fratricidal wars. The main subjects of the book are such well-known figures as [[Osama bin Laden]], [[Ahmad Shah Massoud]], [[Gulbuddin Hekmatyar]], [[Mohammed Omar|Mullah Omar]] and [[Najibullah Zazi]].<ref>[http://culture.pl/en/work/praying-for-rain-wojciech-jagielski Review: ''Praying for Rain'', Culture.pl, managed by Adam Mickiewicz Institute]</ref>\n\nHis book ''Towers of Stone: The Battle of Wills in Chechnya'',<ref name=\"H1000202356\" /> won the Italian [[Literatura Frontera Award]] in 2009 and was published in English by [[Seven Stories Press]].<ref name=\"H1000202356\" /><ref>{{cite book|last=Jagielski|first=Wojciech|year=2009|title=Towers of Stone|publisher=[[Seven Stories Press]]|isbn=978-1-58322-900-2|ref=harv|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/towersofstonebat00jagi}}</ref> Jagielski presents the bitter story of war in [[Chechnya]], and the conflict between groups of warriors with their leaders: [[Shamil Basayev]] and [[Aslan Maskhadov]], against the powerful Russian army.<ref>[http://www.economist.com/node/15063856 \"A small corner, very bloody\"], ''The Economist''</ref>\n\nHis next book, ''The Night Wanderers: Uganda's Children and the Lord's Resistance Army'', about [[child soldier]]s in Uganda, discusses God's Army leader [[Joseph Kony]], who claims that he was possessed by spirits, and former tyrant [[Idi Amin]], who had styled himself as the \"lord of all beings.\"<ref>[http://washingtonpeacecenter.net/node/7496 Washington Peace Center]</ref><ref>[http://culture.pl/en/event/a-reporters-perspective-on-war-jagielskis-night-wanderers-in-the-us \"A Reporter's Perspective on War: Jagielski's Night Wanderers in the US\"], ''Culture''</ref>\n\nHis most recent book to appear in English is ''Burning the Grass: At the Heart of Change in South Africa 1990-2011,'' which examines the 2010 murder of white supremacist South African leader [[Eug\u00e8ne Terre'Blanche]].<ref>[http://catalog.sevenstories.com/products/burning-the-grass-at-the-heart-of-change-in-south-africa-1990-2011]</ref>\n\n== Honors and awards==\n\n*2009: in recognition of his valuable and bold reporting of international issues, [[Rados\u0142aw Sikorski]], Minister of Foreign Affairs, awarded him with the ''[[Bene Merito]]'' honorary distinction.<ref>[http://www.msz.gov.pl/Minister,Radoslaw,Sikorski,awards,Bene,Merito,distinctions,31700.html Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the Republic of Poland]</ref>\n\n\u2022\tPolish Journalists Association (SDP) Awards (1996)\n\n\u2022\tThe Ksawery Pruszy\u0144ski Award of Polish PEN Club (1996)\n\n\u2022\tThe Warsaw Literary Premiere Award (2002)\n\n\u2022\tDariusz Fikus Award (2002)<ref name=\"H1000202356\" />\n\n\u2022\tJ\u00f3zef Tischner Award (2003)\n\n\u2022\tAmber Butterfly in Arkady Fiedler Competition (2003)\n\n\u2022\tMediaTory Student Journalist Award (2008)\n\n\u2022\tLiteratura Frontera Award (2009)<ref name=\"H1000202356\" />\n\nHe was also nominated for the Ryszard Kapu\u015bci\u0144ski Award and the Nike Award.\n\n== References ==\n*\n*[http://ic.galegroup.com/ic/bic1/MagazinesDetailsPage/MagazinesDetailsWindow?failOverType=&query=&prodId=BIC1&windowstate=normal&contentModules=&mode=view&displayGroupName=Magazines&limiter=&currPage=&disableHighlighting=false&displayGroups=&sortBy=&search_within_results=&p=BIC1&action=e&catId=&activityType=&scanId=&documentId=GALE%7CA213982994&source=Bookmark&u=22396_largo&jsid=af72a5cbc553c5c1c8546e556d52ba2d \"A small corner, very bloody; War in the Caucasus.\" ''The Economist'' 12 Dec. 2009: 83(EU). Biography in Context. Web. 7 Jan. 2014. Gale Document Number: GALE|A213982994]\n*[http://ic.galegroup.com/ic/bic1/AcademicJournalsDetailsPage/AcademicJournalsDetailsWindow?failOverType=&query=&prodId=BIC1&windowstate=normal&contentModules=&mode=view&displayGroupName=Journals&limiter=&currPage=&disableHighlighting=false&displayGroups=&sortBy=&search_within_results=&p=BIC1&action=e&catId=&activityType=&scanId=&documentId=GALE%7CA302770693&source=Bookmark&u=22396_largo&jsid=cf24b6c6dfce72547699c3dd09a2485d van de Walle, Nicolas. \"Recent books on international relations: Africa: The Night Wanderers: Uganda's Children and the Lord's Resistance Army.\" ''Foreign Affairs'' 91.5 (2012): 205. Biography in Context. Web. 7 Jan. 2014. Gale Document Number: GALE|A302770693] \n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jagielski, Wojciech}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:Polish journalists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Polish male writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Polish non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Polish male writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century journalists]]\n[[Category:21st-century journalists]]\n[[Category:21st-century Polish non-fiction writers]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wojciech_Jagielski"}
